            <p>University of Pennsylvania&#44;<lb/>
                OFFICE OF THE SECRETARY.<lb/></p>
            <p>May 3&#44; 1887<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Sabato Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>Reverend and dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>It gives me great<lb/> pleasure to inform you that the<lb/> Board of Trustees of the University of<lb/> Pennsylvania resolved this<lb/> day to confer upon you the<lb/> honorary degree of Doctor of<lb/> Laws at the Commencement to<lb/> be held on June the eighth.<lb/></p>
            <p>It is the particular desire of<lb/> the Provost&#91;&#63;&#93; and Trustees that<lb/> you should be present on this<lb/> occasion to receive the degree<lb/> in person&#44; as it is contrary to<lb/> their rules to have it conferred<lb/> <hi rend="underline">in absentia</hi>.  I will have<lb/> the pleasure of sending to<lb/> you in ample time notice of<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the time and place of Com&#45;<lb/>mencement&#44; and as many<lb/> tickets of admission as you<lb/> may desire for distribution<lb/> among your friends.<lb/></p>
            <p>Congratulating you upon<lb/> this well deserved honor&#44;<lb/> I remain<lb/> Very Respectfully Yours<lb/> Jesse G. Burk<lb/> Secretary.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
